        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "7df2d0b293e1f8f6",
        "text": "The Redes de Trueque (Barter Networks) evolved in Argentina in the mid 1990s in response to the economic crisis and collapse of the national currency, the peso. The network created a countrywide chain of community markets, which used their own currency, the ‘Credito’, to facilitate exchange of goods and services. Acceptance of the Creditos of other markets was voluntary, while overall administration and structure of both the network and currency was entirely decentralised."
      },
